  # GitHub Copilot vs Cursor vs Claude Code: Which AI Actually Fixes Production Bugs?
  
  ## _I gave the same production bug to three AI coding assistants. One suggested a band-aid. One created a PR. One rewrote half the service. Only one actually shipped to production._
  
  [![The Unwritten Algorithm](https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fill:64:64/1*rYXgOLZ9U-dfN2aUFJtqiw.png)](https://medium.com/@the_unwritten_algorithm?source=post_page---byline--9485b33131c6---------------------------------------)
  
  [The Unwritten Algorithm](https://medium.com/@the_unwritten_algorithm?source=post_page---byline--9485b33131c6---------------------------------------)
  
  Follow
  
  8 min read
  
  ·
  
  Mar 16, 2026
  
  3
  
  [Listen](https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fplans%3Fdimension%3Dpost_audio_button%26postId%3D9485b33131c6&operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fblog.devgenius.io%2Fgithub-copilot-vs-cursor-vs-claude-code-which-ai-actually-fixes-production-bugs-9485b33131c6&source=---header_actions--9485b33131c6---------------------post_audio_button------------------)
  
  Share
  
  The Slack notification hit at 2:47 AM:
  
  **“Payment processing down. Error rate 34%. Revenue impact estimated $800/min.”**
  
  I rolled out of bed, opened my laptop, and stared at the stack trace. A nil pointer exception in our checkout service. Classic. Should be a 10-minute fix, right?
  
  Wrong.
  
  By the time I’d scrolled through 847 lines of logs, found the actual error (buried in line 623), and traced it back to the PaymentService, it was 3:14 AM. My coffee was cold. My patience was gone.
  
  That’s when I had a stupid idea: what if I just asked AI to fix this?
  
  Not “help me fix this.” Not “explain what’s wrong.” Actually fix it. Write the code. Create the PR. Ship it.
  
  So I ran an experiment. Same bug. Three different AI coding tools. Zero human guidance beyond pasting the error.
  
  Here’s what happened.
  
  ## The Bug That Started This Whole Thing
  
  Before we get into the AI cage match, here’s what broke:
  
  ```
  public class PaymentService {
      public PaymentResult process(Order order) {
          // Get payment method from user preferences
          PaymentMethod method = order.getUser().getPreferences().getPaymentMethod();
  
          // Process payment
          return paymentGateway.charge(method, order.getTotal());
      }
  }
  ```
  
  Looks fine, right? It worked for three months. Processed 47,000 transactions without issue.
  
  Then one user had no payment preferences set. `getPreferences()` returned null. `getPaymentMethod()` exploded. Every subsequent request to the checkout API started throwing 500s.
  
  The fix? Add a null check. Maybe 3 lines of code. Should take 2 minutes.
  
  But finding it? That took 27 minutes of log diving at 3 AM.
  
  That’s the real problem with production bugs. It’s not the fix — it’s the detective work.
  
  ## Round 1: GitHub Copilot
  
  **What I Did:** Opened the PaymentService file. Typed a comment: `// Fix: handle null payment preferences`
  
  **What Copilot Suggested:**
  
  ````
  // Fix: handle null payment preferences
  if (method == null) {
      method = getDefaultPaymentMethod();
  }
  ```
  ````
  
  ````
  **My Reaction:**
  Okay, not terrible. It caught the null check. But where's `getDefaultPaymentMethod()` supposed to come from? Copilot didn't create it. It just assumed it exists.I tried accepting the suggestion. Build failed. Method doesn't exist.**The Problem:**
  Copilot autocompletes code like it autocompletes sentences. It makes assumptions. It fills in the blank with what "looks right" based on patterns. But production code isn't a fill-in-the-blank exercise.**What I Had to Do Manually:**
  - Write the `getDefaultPaymentMethod()` helper
  - Add logging for when this fallback triggers
  - Update tests
  - Write the PR description
  - Deploy**Time Saved:** Maybe 30 seconds of typing.**Would I Ship This to Production?** Not without spending another 15 minutes filling in Copilot's assumptions.---## Round 2: Cursor**What I Did:**
  Selected the entire PaymentService class. Opened Cursor's chat. Typed: "Fix the nil pointer bug in this code."**What Cursor Did:**It read the code. It highlighted the problem line. Then it did something interesting—it asked me a question:
  ```
  I found a potential nil pointer at line 4.
  How should we handle missing payment preferences?A) Use a default payment method
  B) Return an error to the user
  C) Log and skip payment processing
  ````
  
  Wait, what?
  
  An AI just asked me to make a product decision. That’s… actually smart?
  
  **What I Chose:** Option B (return error to user)
  
  **What Cursor Generated:**
  
  ````
  public class PaymentService {
      public PaymentResult process(Order order) {
          UserPreferences prefs = order.getUser().getPreferences();
  
          if (prefs == null || prefs.getPaymentMethod() == null) {
              logger.warn("Missing payment preferences for user: {}",
                  order.getUser().getId());
              return PaymentResult.error("Please add a payment method to continue");
          }
  
          PaymentMethod method = prefs.getPaymentMethod();
          return paymentGateway.charge(method, order.getTotal());
      }
  }
  ```
  ````
  
  ````
  Plus:
  - Updated the `PaymentResult` class with an `.error()` factory method
  - Added logging
  - Suggested a unit test
  - Created a Git commit message**My Reaction:**
  This is closer. Way closer. The code is defensive. The error message is user-friendly. The logging makes sense.But here's the catch: Cursor didn't create a PR. It didn't push to GitHub. It generated code and stopped.**What I Had to Do Manually:**
  - Review the changes
  - Run tests locally
  - Create the branch
  - Push to GitHub
  - Open the PR
  - Add reviewers**Time Saved:** About 10 minutes of writing + thinking.**Would I Ship This?** Yes, but I'd still need to babysit the deployment.---## Round 3: Claude Code (via ProdRescue)**What I Did:**
  This one was different. I didn't open an IDE. I didn't paste code.I had the full incident context in Slack. 200 messages of engineers debugging. Logs. Stack traces. Timeline.I typed: `@ProdRescue analyze this thread and suggest a fix`**What Claude Code Did:**First, it read the entire Slack thread. Not just the code—the context. Engineers saying "checkout API is timing out." Logs showing the nil pointer. My message at 3:02 AM: "This started when we deployed the user preferences migration."Then it generated an incident report:
  ```
  Root Cause: Nil pointer in PaymentService.process()
  when user preferences are null.Evidence:
  [1] Stack trace at 02:47:12 - line 4 of PaymentService
  [6] Database migration logs - preferences.payment_method
      set to nullable in migration #847
  [12] Error spike correlates with migration deploy timestampContributing Factor: Migration made payment_method nullable
  but code still assumes non-null.Suggested Fix: Add null safety check + user-facing error
  ````
  
  **Then It Offered to Fix It:**
  
  “Want me to create a PR with the fix?”
  
  I clicked yes.
  
  **What It Generated:**
  
  The same defensive code Cursor wrote. But then it did more:
  
  1. **Searched my GitHub repo** for similar null-check patterns
  2. **Found 3 other places** in the codebase with the same vulnerability
  3. **Created a branch:**`fix/payment-preferences-null-safety`
  4. **Committed 4 files:**
  
  - PaymentService.java (the fix)
  - PaymentServiceTest.java (test coverage)
  - UserPreferencesService.java (related fix)
  - OrderService.java (related fix)
  
  **Opened a PR** with:
  
  - Description linking to the incident
  - Risk assessment (“Low risk — defensive code”)
  - Deployment notes (“Safe to deploy immediately”)
  
  **My Reaction:**
  
  Wait, it found three other bugs I didn’t know existed?
  
  I reviewed the PR. All four fixes were correct. The tests passed. The risk assessment was accurate.
  
  **What I Had to Do Manually:**
  
  - Click “Approve”
  - Click “Merge”
  
  **Time Saved:** 45 minutes (if you count finding the other 3 bugs I would’ve missed).
  
  ## Get The Unwritten Algorithm’s stories in your inbox
  
  Join Medium for free to get updates from this writer.
  
  Subscribe
  
  Subscribe
  
  Remember me for faster sign in
  
  **Would I Ship This?** I did. It’s in production right now.
  
  ## The Real Difference: Context vs Code Completion
  
  Here’s what I learned from this experiment:
  
  **GitHub Copilot** thinks in autocomplete. It sees code, suggests more code. It doesn’t understand the problem — it pattern-matches the solution.
  
  **Cursor** thinks in conversation. It asks questions. It clarifies intent. But it stops at code generation. You’re still the one who ships it.
  
  **Claude Code** thinks in incidents. It reads the whole story — logs, context, timeline. Then it fixes not just the bug you found, but the bugs you didn’t.
  
  The difference isn’t intelligence. It’s scope.
  
  Copilot sees a function. Cursor sees a file. Claude Code sees a problem.
  
  ## When to Use Which Tool
  
  I’m not saying one is “better.” I’m saying they’re built for different jobs.
  
  ## Use Copilot When:
  
  - You’re writing new code from scratch
  - You know exactly what you need
  - Autocomplete speeds up typing
  - The code pattern is common (loops, CRUD, boilerplate)
  
  **Don’t Use Copilot When:**
  
  - You’re debugging production
  - The context is scattered
  - The fix requires understanding the system
  
  ## Use Cursor When:
  
  - You want to think through options
  - The fix isn’t obvious
  - You need help structuring the solution
  - You like chat-driven development
  
  **Don’t Use Cursor When:**
  
  - You’re in a hurry
  - You need end-to-end automation
  - The bug context is in Slack/logs, not code
  
  ## Use Claude Code When:
  
  - Production is broken
  - Context is scattered (Slack, logs, multiple files)
  - You need the full fix, not just code suggestions
  - You want it to find related issues
  - You’re tired and want AI to handle it
  
  **Don’t Use Claude Code When:**
  
  - You’re prototyping
  - Speed matters more than correctness
  - The problem is small and well-defined
  
  ## The Uncomfortable Truth About AI Code Assistants
  
  None of these tools “fix bugs” the way we think.
  
  Copilot writes code you were about to write anyway. Cursor helps you think through code you’re writing. Claude Code automates code you wish someone else would write.
  
  They’re all useful. None of them replace thinking.
  
  But here’s the thing: at 3 AM, when your checkout API is bleeding revenue and you’re staring at 847 lines of logs, **I don’t want to think.** I want the bug fixed. I want the PR created. I want to go back to sleep.
  
  That’s the job Claude Code does better than the others. Not because it’s smarter. Because it’s built for a different moment — the moment when “helping me code” isn’t enough. I need it done.
  
  ## What This Means for Your Workflow
  
  After three months of using all three tools in production, here’s my setup:
  
  **Daily Development:**
  
  - Copilot runs in the background (autocomplete on steroids)
  - Cursor open for thinking through complex logic
  
  **Incident Response:**
  
  - Claude Code via ProdRescue for anything production-related
  - Especially when context is in Slack and I’m too tired to translate it into code
  
  **The Result:**
  
  - MTTR down from 42 minutes to 18 minutes average
  - Fewer “oops we missed a related bug” followup incidents
  - More sleep
  
  Your mileage may vary. But if you’re debugging production at 3 AM more than once a month, Claude Code pays for itself in saved sanity.
  
  ## The Experiment Continues
  
  I’m still running this test. Every production bug gets the same treatment:
  
  1. Try Copilot’s suggestion
  2. Try Cursor’s approach
  3. Try Claude Code’s fix
  
  So far? Claude Code has shipped 14/14 fixes without modification. Cursor needed tweaks on 8/14. Copilot needed full rewrites on 11/14.
  
  But here’s the weird part: I still use all three. Because they’re not competing — they’re complementary.
  
  Copilot makes me faster at writing. Cursor makes me smarter at designing. Claude Code makes me saner at firefighting.
  
  Pick the right tool for the moment. Not the tool that’s “best.”
  
  ## Try It Yourself
  
  Want to run your own comparison? Here’s a production bug template you can test on all three:
  
  **Bug:** Nil pointer when user.preferences is null **Context:** Happened after database migration **Files affected:** Unknown (that’s the test)
  
  See which tool:
  
  1. Finds the bug fastest
  2. Suggests the best fix
  3. Catches related issues
  4. Actually ships to production
  
  My bet? You’ll end up using all three, just like me.
  
