  ![I Tested Cursor, GitHub Copilot, and Claude Code. One Wins Clearly.](https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*uQnGpn5uIB1GxNUOiGeD2Q.png)
  
  I used to doubt AI coding tools for a long time. Then I tested them properly and changed my mind completely. That article got more traffic than anything else I have written.
  
  Since then, three tools have pulled ahead of the pack. Cursor, GitHub Copilot, and Claude Code. Every developer I know is using at least one of them. Most are arguing about which one is best.
  
  So I ran a proper test. Same tasks, same codebase, same developer. Three weeks across real production work, not contrived examples. Here is what I found.
  
  **Friend link for nonmembers-** [**https://medium.com/@inprogrammer/i-tested-cursor-github-copilot-and-claude-code-one-wins-clearly-a6f19828f32f?sk=10103bd009328cc5249d70cef32d0d13**](https://medium.com/@inprogrammer/i-tested-cursor-github-copilot-and-claude-code-one-wins-clearly-a6f19828f32f?sk=10103bd009328cc5249d70cef32d0d13)
  
  ## The Test Setup
  
  I was building a FastAPI application with a PostgreSQL database, a Redis cache, and several third party API integrations. A realistic mix of the kind of work most Python backend developers do every day.
  
  For each tool, I tracked four things. How fast it completed the task. How correct the output was on the first attempt. How well it handled context across multiple files. And how much it slowed me down when it got things wrong.
  
  That last metric matters more than most comparisons acknowledge. A tool that is fast but wrong frequently costs more time than a slower tool that is right consistently.
  
  ## GitHub Copilot
  
  GitHub Copilot is the most widely used AI coding tool in the world. It lives inside your editor as an autocomplete engine, suggesting the next line or next block of code as you type.
  
  **What it does well:**
  
  Copilot is genuinely excellent at pattern completion. Boilerplate code, repetitive structures, and anything that follows a predictable pattern comes out correctly almost every time.
  
  ```
  # I typed this
  class UserRepository:
      def __init__(self, db: AsyncSession):
          self.db = db
  ```
  
  ```
      async def get_by_id(self, user_id: int) -> User | None:
  ```
  
